WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.545 --> 00:00:03.965
Hi, I am Patricia Pinot.

2
00:00:04.285 --> 00:00:05.365
I am an economist

3
00:00:05.625 --> 00:00:09.605
and executive director at MMT UK Policy Research Group,

4
00:00:10.285 --> 00:00:13.685
a think tank that produces policy papers based on an

5
00:00:13.845 --> 00:00:16.165
accurate understanding of the UK monetary system

6
00:00:16.545 --> 00:00:19.565
to advance public purpose in the United Kingdom.

7
00:00:30.845 --> 00:00:33.875
Today, the main way governments manage inflation is

8
00:00:33.875 --> 00:00:35.955
by raising and lowering interest rates.

9
00:00:36.625 --> 00:00:38.675
What most people don't realize is

10
00:00:38.675 --> 00:00:41.715
that this system involves our policy makers effectively

11
00:00:41.995 --> 00:00:44.755
building in and maintaining a certain level

12
00:00:44.815 --> 00:00:46.355
of unemployment in the economy.

13
00:00:46.735 --> 00:00:48.675
Policy makers understand it like this

14
00:00:49.665 --> 00:00:51.115
when unemployment goes up,

15
00:00:51.185 --> 00:00:52.995
workers have less bargaining power

16
00:00:53.135 --> 00:00:54.555
and wages grow more slowly,

17
00:00:55.065 --> 00:00:57.155
thereby reducing the risk of inflation.

18
00:00:57.585 --> 00:00:59.075
When unemployment goes down,

19
00:00:59.185 --> 00:01:01.315
workers have more bargaining power

20
00:01:01.695 --> 00:01:03.195
and wages tend to rise faster,

21
00:01:03.565 --> 00:01:05.475
which increases the risk of inflation.

22
00:01:06.225 --> 00:01:08.515
This is rarely discussed in public discourse,

23
00:01:09.175 --> 00:01:12.675
but deliberately allowing unemployment to rise is central to

24
00:01:12.695 --> 00:01:15.835
how inflation is controlled in a neoliberal economy.

25
00:01:17.455 --> 00:01:19.955
The Problem with this paradigm is that it takes

26
00:01:19.975 --> 00:01:23.195
for granted that some people must be permanently excluded

27
00:01:23.385 --> 00:01:24.555
from economic life,

28
00:01:25.295 --> 00:01:27.515
but unemployment is not just a statistic.

29
00:01:28.015 --> 00:01:31.675
It imposes a real and lasting human and societal costs

30
00:01:32.625 --> 00:01:36.435
Without Access to jobs, people face social exclusion

31
00:01:36.775 --> 00:01:39.555
and risk, long-term harm to their own wellbeing,

32
00:01:39.735 --> 00:01:41.115
and that of their communities.

33
00:01:42.125 --> 00:01:43.315
Using unemployment

34
00:01:43.315 --> 00:01:46.235
to manage prices is not only socially harmful,

35
00:01:46.695 --> 00:01:50.195
it is also a very inefficient way to stabilize the economy.

36
00:01:51.315 --> 00:01:52.495
My name is Pina Chen.

37
00:01:52.715 --> 00:01:55.055
I'm a professor of economics at Bard College, uh,

38
00:01:55.075 --> 00:01:57.255
the president of the Leave Economics Institute,

39
00:01:57.795 --> 00:02:02.615
and I've authored in 2020, uh, the case for a job guarantee,

40
00:02:03.225 --> 00:02:06.455
which outlines the economic case

41
00:02:06.875 --> 00:02:08.935
and the various benefits for the program.

42
00:02:09.075 --> 00:02:11.655
But I've worked also at the policy level

43
00:02:12.335 --> 00:02:14.375
studying real life employment programs

44
00:02:14.915 --> 00:02:18.615
and working with governments on thinking about what kind of,

45
00:02:18.675 --> 00:02:21.615
uh, design features programs, uh, as this might have

46
00:02:22.565 --> 00:02:23.825
on the efficiency question.

47
00:02:23.965 --> 00:02:25.985
You know, we have so narrowly, uh,

48
00:02:26.255 --> 00:02:30.585
defined a society efficiency is something that, um,

49
00:02:31.515 --> 00:02:35.505
falls in, in this worldview that, uh, as long

50
00:02:35.505 --> 00:02:37.025
as there's some kind of return

51
00:02:37.045 --> 00:02:40.105
and usually a financial return to that activity, then that

52
00:02:40.135 --> 00:02:41.145
what makes it useful.

53
00:02:41.525 --> 00:02:44.425
But in fact, if you, if you really look at

54
00:02:44.425 --> 00:02:47.945
what makes a good society, uh, we would recognize

55
00:02:47.945 --> 00:02:50.105
that there's so many employment opportunities,

56
00:02:50.285 --> 00:02:53.905
so many jobs on which we rely that are not there for profit,

57
00:02:54.255 --> 00:02:56.265
that are absolutely fundamental

58
00:02:56.445 --> 00:02:58.665
to the smooth functioning of a society.

59
00:02:59.345 --> 00:03:01.805
So we can think about employment in healthcare.

60
00:03:01.985 --> 00:03:05.365
We can think about employment in climate work, in

61
00:03:05.515 --> 00:03:08.165
Various in Education, where the,

62
00:03:08.165 --> 00:03:09.485
the returns might not be visible.

63
00:03:09.715 --> 00:03:13.305
They may not be immediately financial, their returns

64
00:03:13.305 --> 00:03:15.265
to the greater wellbeing of the society.

65
00:03:15.725 --> 00:03:18.425
And so we really, uh, need

66
00:03:18.425 --> 00:03:19.825
to be thinking in broader terms about

67
00:03:19.825 --> 00:03:22.145
what makes the good life and what kind

68
00:03:22.145 --> 00:03:24.145
of employment is required

69
00:03:24.285 --> 00:03:27.025
to support the well functioning of an economy.

70
00:03:28.205 --> 00:03:30.985
And I think the final one that's really worth mentioning is

71
00:03:30.985 --> 00:03:33.945
that a lot of social problems are related

72
00:03:34.045 --> 00:03:35.665
to the absence of decent work.

73
00:03:36.405 --> 00:03:40.865
Uh, we know very well from research that, um, mental

74
00:03:41.045 --> 00:03:45.825
and physical health deteriorates quite rapidly, um, for,

75
00:03:45.965 --> 00:03:49.785
uh, uh, for those who who don't have stable, uh,

76
00:03:49.805 --> 00:03:50.865
or any employment.

77
00:03:51.405 --> 00:03:54.745
Um, we know that there's such a thing as economic crime,

78
00:03:54.885 --> 00:03:58.425
you know, petty theft, um, and other, uh, problems.

79
00:03:58.885 --> 00:04:02.905
Uh, we, um, so not only are people, uh, sicker and weaker,

80
00:04:02.965 --> 00:04:05.145
but that creates the very conditions

81
00:04:05.145 --> 00:04:07.105
that might prevent them from then taking

82
00:04:07.105 --> 00:04:08.545
employment subsequently.

83
00:04:08.925 --> 00:04:13.305
So the, the job guarantee is really effective at addressing

84
00:04:13.305 --> 00:04:17.405
those social costs, but not only eliminating them,

85
00:04:17.425 --> 00:04:19.005
but also preventing them.

86
00:04:19.225 --> 00:04:20.365
And I think this is one thing

87
00:04:20.365 --> 00:04:24.445
that's missing in our overall approach to economic problems.

88
00:04:24.465 --> 00:04:26.085
We don't have preventative solutions.

89
00:04:26.425 --> 00:04:30.885
We always, you know, allow unemployment to develop,

90
00:04:31.065 --> 00:04:32.565
and then we scratch our heads,

91
00:04:32.625 --> 00:04:35.285
and then we think, what golly can we do

92
00:04:35.585 --> 00:04:37.405
to bring those people back into the lame

93
00:04:37.405 --> 00:04:38.765
or market as opposed

94
00:04:38.785 --> 00:04:41.565
to simply have an open-ended employment opportunity

95
00:04:42.065 --> 00:04:45.045
and then prevent the, the problems associated?

96
00:04:45.045 --> 00:04:46.725
Especially with long-term unemployment,

97
00:04:47.835 --> 00:04:50.435
A job guarantee offers a much more humane

98
00:04:50.455 --> 00:04:52.715
and effective way to stabilize the economy.

99
00:04:53.345 --> 00:04:55.875
Instead of controlling inflation through unemployment,

100
00:04:56.255 --> 00:04:59.235
the government links spending directly to productive work

101
00:04:59.615 --> 00:05:02.155
by offering a job to anyone who wants one

102
00:05:02.665 --> 00:05:05.915
with a job guarantee involuntary unemployment is effectively

103
00:05:06.005 --> 00:05:07.995
eliminated anyone willing

104
00:05:08.055 --> 00:05:09.995
and able to work is able

105
00:05:10.015 --> 00:05:12.755
to access a job providing a minimum level

106
00:05:12.775 --> 00:05:13.995
of income and security.

107
00:05:15.015 --> 00:05:17.155
The wage for This job should be set at a level

108
00:05:17.155 --> 00:05:18.915
that supports a minimum decent standard

109
00:05:18.915 --> 00:05:20.155
of living in our society.

110
00:05:20.655 --> 00:05:23.595
And for this purpose, we can use respected benchmarks such

111
00:05:23.595 --> 00:05:25.155
as the Joseph Roundtree Foundation's

112
00:05:25.225 --> 00:05:26.635
minimum income standard.

113
00:05:27.455 --> 00:05:30.515
The program establishes a wage flow across the whole

114
00:05:30.515 --> 00:05:34.995
economy, so workers are no longer forced to accept low pay,

115
00:05:35.415 --> 00:05:38.715
unsafe or precarious working conditions just to get by.

116
00:05:39.185 --> 00:05:40.595
This is Especially important

117
00:05:40.735 --> 00:05:42.075
for people in the gig economy

118
00:05:42.335 --> 00:05:45.555
who are still in zero hours contracts or in other insecure

119
00:05:45.555 --> 00:05:48.835
and poorly protected forms of work to retain workers.

120
00:05:49.515 --> 00:05:50.755
Employers must offer pay

121
00:05:50.855 --> 00:05:52.795
and conditions that are at least as good

122
00:05:52.895 --> 00:05:55.915
as the job guarantee alternative, while those who prefer

123
00:05:55.915 --> 00:05:59.325
to stay in these kinds of jobs for flexibility purposes,

124
00:05:59.465 --> 00:06:00.685
remain free to do so.

125
00:06:02.825 --> 00:06:06.125
My name is Daniel Kotzer. I am an economist.

126
00:06:06.245 --> 00:06:07.965
I actually the chief economist

127
00:06:07.965 --> 00:06:10.125
of the International Trade Union Confederation,

128
00:06:10.785 --> 00:06:14.365
and I have a long experience in labor market issues

129
00:06:14.465 --> 00:06:17.805
and in relation to more precisely to job guarantee,

130
00:06:18.525 --> 00:06:19.685
I was in the team

131
00:06:19.685 --> 00:06:23.165
that drafted the first employment guarantee program in

132
00:06:23.165 --> 00:06:25.645
Argentina that was called the Plan Hefe Yogurt.

133
00:06:26.515 --> 00:06:28.245
That was the plan implemented

134
00:06:28.245 --> 00:06:31.965
after the crisis in 2002, 2003 in Argentina.

135
00:06:34.675 --> 00:06:38.725
Argentina underwent in the nineties a very typical

136
00:06:39.335 --> 00:06:43.605
neoliberal Washington consensus type of policies that

137
00:06:44.345 --> 00:06:46.605
aod the productive capacity of the country

138
00:06:46.755 --> 00:06:49.445
that reduce the formal employment,

139
00:06:50.085 --> 00:06:52.045
increase unemployment significantly.

140
00:06:52.705 --> 00:06:55.045
At the same time, that also increased poverty.

141
00:06:56.025 --> 00:06:59.765
By the end of the 2001, the level

142
00:06:59.825 --> 00:07:03.005
of unemployment was almost 25%.

143
00:07:03.315 --> 00:07:05.805
Poverty was above 55%,

144
00:07:06.465 --> 00:07:09.205
and the unrest was so massive

145
00:07:09.675 --> 00:07:14.645
that induced social protests that, uh, ended up with the,

146
00:07:14.755 --> 00:07:17.725
with the changes of change in governments

147
00:07:18.065 --> 00:07:22.045
and also the need of a major public intervention in order

148
00:07:22.145 --> 00:07:23.245
to reduce the crisis.

149
00:07:24.345 --> 00:07:26.045
So what specifically are you trying

150
00:07:26.045 --> 00:07:27.085
to achieve with the program?

151
00:07:28.875 --> 00:07:31.285
With the program that was, as I mentioned,

152
00:07:31.595 --> 00:07:34.645
what we were trying was to cover a large

153
00:07:34.945 --> 00:07:39.285
and increasing unemployment in the country where we saw

154
00:07:39.285 --> 00:07:40.325
that month

155
00:07:40.335 --> 00:07:43.485
after month, the number of people looking for a job

156
00:07:43.545 --> 00:07:45.445
and without having a job, was increasing.

157
00:07:45.905 --> 00:07:48.765
But also we saw that many people was

158
00:07:48.875 --> 00:07:51.165
what we may call discouraged workers,

159
00:07:51.315 --> 00:07:53.725
that they didn't even go to look for a job

160
00:07:53.725 --> 00:07:55.525
because they found no opportunities.

161
00:07:56.145 --> 00:08:00.045
So the objective was to provide the job in order to

162
00:08:00.685 --> 00:08:03.205
transfer an income to these households, to these people,

163
00:08:03.625 --> 00:08:04.965
and reduce poverty

164
00:08:05.345 --> 00:08:08.925
and unemployment rate, which are very, I would say,

165
00:08:09.845 --> 00:08:14.245
sensitive, uh, indicators of, uh, the political, uh,

166
00:08:14.745 --> 00:08:17.725
the political distress of the population.

167
00:08:18.785 --> 00:08:21.045
And, and what were the biggest challenges you found

168
00:08:21.115 --> 00:08:22.245
when introducing the program?

169
00:08:23.035 --> 00:08:26.205
Well, the challenges are at, at different levels.

170
00:08:26.385 --> 00:08:29.365
You know, the first challenge is to convince politicians

171
00:08:29.475 --> 00:08:32.805
that you are giving something

172
00:08:32.825 --> 00:08:36.605
that's more called like an entitlement rather than a

173
00:08:36.675 --> 00:08:39.685
traditional social policy of targeting

174
00:08:39.685 --> 00:08:41.325
and allocating in the different groups.

175
00:08:41.825 --> 00:08:43.885
So that was the, the, the, the first thing.

176
00:08:43.905 --> 00:08:46.085
The second challenge was try to assess

177
00:08:46.385 --> 00:08:48.565
how many people was going to go into the program.

178
00:08:49.555 --> 00:08:53.525
Another challenge was how to organize the people

179
00:08:53.525 --> 00:08:56.165
that would go into the program to avoid, you know,

180
00:08:56.465 --> 00:08:59.685
the political, uh, patronizing of allocating

181
00:08:59.705 --> 00:09:02.765
to this one yes, and to this other no, just try

182
00:09:02.765 --> 00:09:03.805
to make universal.

183
00:09:04.145 --> 00:09:08.005
And then the, the other challenge was to find activities

184
00:09:08.005 --> 00:09:11.165
that would be useful for the community

185
00:09:11.945 --> 00:09:12.945
In the uk. Some

186
00:09:12.945 --> 00:09:14.525
programs have been described

187
00:09:14.525 --> 00:09:16.685
as job guarantees in the past, such

188
00:09:16.685 --> 00:09:18.725
as labor's youth guarantee, for example.

189
00:09:19.225 --> 00:09:22.645
But this differs significantly from a universal public job

190
00:09:22.645 --> 00:09:24.325
guarantee to begin with.

191
00:09:24.325 --> 00:09:27.485
People are often forced to take part, risking the loss

192
00:09:27.485 --> 00:09:30.125
of benefits if they refuse jobs that they did not choose,

193
00:09:30.585 --> 00:09:33.565
and are given little chance to gain useful experience

194
00:09:33.745 --> 00:09:35.685
or improve their long-term prospects.

195
00:09:35.915 --> 00:09:39.205
They're also not universally available, usually restricted

196
00:09:39.205 --> 00:09:42.445
by quotas and often paying only the legal minimum wage,

197
00:09:42.655 --> 00:09:44.725
which many agree is not enough

198
00:09:44.785 --> 00:09:47.885
to meet basic living standards, where still many

199
00:09:47.885 --> 00:09:50.405
of these schemes allow for-profit companies

200
00:09:50.625 --> 00:09:52.205
to access subsidized labor.

201
00:09:52.675 --> 00:09:55.085
This creates a risk of displacing

202
00:09:55.765 --> 00:09:58.525
existing non-subsidized workers rather than creating

203
00:09:58.745 --> 00:10:00.205
new socially useful work.

204
00:10:02.405 --> 00:10:06.805
I would say every single country could afford this type

205
00:10:06.805 --> 00:10:10.165
of program, number one, because they're counter cyclical.

206
00:10:10.635 --> 00:10:14.645
Yeah. The, that's the, the, the, the best idea of this type

207
00:10:14.645 --> 00:10:17.445
of program is to have it always implemented.

208
00:10:17.865 --> 00:10:21.645
So you have like a buffer stock, you know, of, of jobs

209
00:10:21.715 --> 00:10:24.005
that they are available when the economy goes down,

210
00:10:24.005 --> 00:10:27.405
people move from the private sector to this type of program,

211
00:10:27.585 --> 00:10:31.365
and then when the economy goes up, they move to the, to the,

212
00:10:31.425 --> 00:10:33.725
to the other side of the, of the market.

213
00:10:34.305 --> 00:10:37.205
So, uh, if they work as a buffer stock,

214
00:10:37.305 --> 00:10:40.205
you will never need huge amounts of money

215
00:10:40.205 --> 00:10:43.125
because it will be precisely to reduce the cycle.

216
00:10:43.125 --> 00:10:47.565
Like, uh, uh, many economies, they, they,

217
00:10:47.595 --> 00:10:50.285
they point out as a, one of the objectives

218
00:10:50.305 --> 00:10:51.485
of this type of program.

219
00:10:52.305 --> 00:10:54.845
So, uh, I don't think that the cost

220
00:10:54.845 --> 00:10:56.885
of a program is the main, the main topic.

221
00:10:57.155 --> 00:11:00.765
They are, I would say, the best, eh,

222
00:11:01.225 --> 00:11:04.885
social policy at the very reasonable cost in terms

223
00:11:04.885 --> 00:11:06.405
of the fiscal space needed.

224
00:11:07.745 --> 00:11:10.165
The job quarantee is, uh, uh,

225
00:11:10.165 --> 00:11:12.285
simply put a direct employment approach.

226
00:11:12.985 --> 00:11:17.005
Um, it is an approach that employs, uh, those

227
00:11:17.265 --> 00:11:22.045
who are looking for, uh, good jobs in, uh, positions

228
00:11:22.045 --> 00:11:24.485
that, uh, do public service

229
00:11:25.025 --> 00:11:27.525
or address challenges such as the climate challenges.

230
00:11:27.525 --> 00:11:32.005
The job Guity is conceived as a broader program, uh,

231
00:11:32.025 --> 00:11:35.725
for employment, one that, uh, will be redirected

232
00:11:35.725 --> 00:11:36.845
to various social needs.

233
00:11:36.845 --> 00:11:38.965
They could be care needs, they could be, uh,

234
00:11:38.965 --> 00:11:41.405
environmental needs, they could be community needs.

235
00:11:41.745 --> 00:11:45.525
But I think that probably the most urgent, um, uh,

236
00:11:45.525 --> 00:11:47.005
threat we all have to address

237
00:11:47.105 --> 00:11:49.045
as society is the climate threat.

238
00:11:49.585 --> 00:11:51.765
And that ripples through our communities,

239
00:11:51.765 --> 00:11:53.610
that affects the way we care for each other.

240
00:11:53.675 --> 00:11:56.365
That affects the way our, you know, our hotels

241
00:11:56.365 --> 00:11:59.405
and cities can be livable communities.

242
00:11:59.785 --> 00:12:04.525
And so the job guarantee essentially thinks through the kind

243
00:12:04.525 --> 00:12:08.165
of investments that are necessary, um, for, uh,

244
00:12:08.165 --> 00:12:10.565
for a climate work, and then creates those opportunities.

245
00:12:10.945 --> 00:12:14.805
We can think of, uh, small projects like, um, you know,

246
00:12:14.845 --> 00:12:15.965
greening our cities.

247
00:12:16.265 --> 00:12:19.685
You can think of trees as the lungs of our towns

248
00:12:19.705 --> 00:12:20.805
and our communities.

249
00:12:20.865 --> 00:12:23.245
We can think about community gardens

250
00:12:23.245 --> 00:12:25.765
that provide locally sourced food

251
00:12:25.765 --> 00:12:30.125
that is not dependent on supply chains across the globe

252
00:12:30.425 --> 00:12:34.805
and produce sustainable quality food for everyone.

253
00:12:34.905 --> 00:12:39.125
We can think of large scale investments, um, as I said,

254
00:12:39.145 --> 00:12:43.965
you know, installation of panels, solar panels of, uh,

255
00:12:43.965 --> 00:12:47.965
wind turbines, various other solutions to energy production.

256
00:12:48.265 --> 00:12:51.525
So we can think, uh, very broadly of what is required.

257
00:12:51.785 --> 00:12:55.765
And the job guarantee doesn't rely on incentives waiting

258
00:12:55.905 --> 00:12:58.605
around for the private sector

259
00:12:59.145 --> 00:13:02.605
to figure out the precise return in order to direct

260
00:13:03.185 --> 00:13:04.565
its activities in that area.

261
00:13:04.945 --> 00:13:06.045
It is a very direct

262
00:13:06.145 --> 00:13:09.285
and straightforward, uh, approach to the problem.

263
00:13:10.065 --> 00:13:12.405
In fact, two problems, the problem of unemployment

264
00:13:12.465 --> 00:13:14.605
and the problem of, of the green transition.

265
00:13:15.785 --> 00:13:18.025
A universal public job guarantee is

266
00:13:18.025 --> 00:13:19.145
fundamentally different.

267
00:13:19.935 --> 00:13:22.065
It's nationally funded and delivered locally.

268
00:13:22.325 --> 00:13:25.345
So communities decide what work is needed

269
00:13:25.485 --> 00:13:26.745
and valuable in their areas.

270
00:13:27.415 --> 00:13:29.825
Funding expands where more people need jobs

271
00:13:30.045 --> 00:13:32.865
and contracts as the economy recovers, directing,

272
00:13:32.865 --> 00:13:35.865
support exactly where and when it is required.

273
00:13:36.735 --> 00:13:39.905
Instead of paying the high social costs of unemployment,

274
00:13:40.285 --> 00:13:43.145
we invest in useful work, making better use

275
00:13:43.145 --> 00:13:46.545
of public resources while strengthening local economies.

276
00:13:49.115 --> 00:13:51.305
Local priorities shape job creation,

277
00:13:51.525 --> 00:13:54.425
making the program more responsive and democratic.

278
00:13:55.685 --> 00:13:58.345
The program is open to nonprofits, cooperatives,

279
00:13:58.345 --> 00:14:01.225
and social enterprises that meet clear standards.

280
00:14:01.885 --> 00:14:03.705
All jobs follow national

281
00:14:03.725 --> 00:14:05.625
and local guidelines to ensure

282
00:14:05.625 --> 00:14:09.065
that they provide real community benefit, build skills,

283
00:14:09.445 --> 00:14:12.105
and do not replace existing public sector roles

284
00:14:12.605 --> 00:14:14.105
or unfairly compete

285
00:14:14.255 --> 00:14:16.185
with well provisioned commercial activity.

286
00:14:16.775 --> 00:14:20.065
Most importantly, people themselves can take the lead

287
00:14:20.655 --> 00:14:23.345
individuals or even small teams of up

288
00:14:23.345 --> 00:14:24.985
to five people can propose

289
00:14:25.045 --> 00:14:27.385
and deliver projects that address local needs

290
00:14:27.735 --> 00:14:29.785
with support from their local authorities.

291
00:14:30.325 --> 00:14:32.945
The result is practical, community-driven work

292
00:14:33.255 --> 00:14:36.465
that unlocks local talent, strengthens neighborhoods,

293
00:14:36.965 --> 00:14:39.865
and ensures that everyone can access decent,

294
00:14:40.195 --> 00:14:41.425
meaningful employment.

295
00:14:41.965 --> 00:14:45.985
In the age of ai that has become more important than ever.
